The plate carriers are adjustable from Small up to XX-Large
MIL-A-46100 steel is Military spec armor. MIL-A 46100 armor is used to stop high velocity projectiles (HVPs). This particular grade military spec armor steel is especially useful to protect structures or vehicles from sniper fire or any form of weapon that will emit the HVPs depending on the threat level, various thicknesses of steel may be required to protect vital organs.
The measurement of the plates are 1/4" also not to mention tested by the U.S Army test labs. This particular armor is made to military spec and it is designed to withstand higher caliber rounds.
I used a .308 rifle and a .223 at The Mil-A-46100 plates at 30 and 50 yards. Then shot it with AK 47 50rnds, 5.56 30rnds, .357/9mm/45cal, 7.62x54R, still no penetration. Not to mention shot at it with a .45 handgun still no penetration. This will not fail to disappoint as it this is one of the best quality steel out there. This is much more sophisticated steel compared to AR500, AR500 is level 3 and is target material. Our Armor is Level 4. I've shot at our Mil-A-46100 Armor multiple times with different rifles and Handguns and it still holds up. You could attach MOLLE gear to this vest such as your Hydration water Carrier, Rifle and Handgun Magazine pouches, Radio pouches, EMT Medical pouches and etc. Thank you for viewing!

title: For Sale:  Steyr M9-A1, in Excellent Condition
postcontent:
Up for sale is my slightly used Steyr M9-A1 9MM pistol.  This is a later model, with a roller bearing in the striker channel for a smoother and more consistent trigger pull.  It is in excellent condition, and included are three 17 rd. magazines, the original case & papers, and keys for the built-in trigger lock.  Also included as a bonus is a stainless steel BT guide rod (not installed), which adds a little extra weight to the muzzle to further reduce the minimal muzzle flip this pistol has.

For those not familiar with the M9-A1, here are some facts and some comparisons with the "Other Austrian Pistol", the Glock 19:  The Steyr has a similar grip angle, but a smaller diameter and much more ergomonic grip shape. The Steyr has a 4mm lower bore axis, for less muzzle flip and less perceived recoil. The Steyr has a steel frame incorporating longer frame rails and the trigger / sear mechanism (very solid and precise).  This steel frame fits into the polymer grip as a module.  The glock uses its polymer grip as a frame to locate & hold the trigger mechanism, and the shorter frame rails are molded into the polymer grip. The Steyr uses unique fast acquisition trapezoidal / triangle combat sights which are made of steel (easily replaced if you prefer standard rectangular or night sights).  The glock has plastic sights. The Steyr has a shorter trigger pull, with a quicker reset. The Steyr has a two round greater standard magazine capacity (17 rds versus 15). The Steyr has a built-in keyed trigger lock as an additional safety feature. The Steyr was initially designed for the .40 S&W, and then adapted for the less powerful 9mm.  The Steyr's barrel  has a fully supported chamber, and standard rifling to allow use of non-jacketed bullets, while the glock's chamber is not fully supported, and their rifling requires jacketed bullets.  
My price for everything listed is $525.  I prefer to sell, but would consider trades for other firearms, specifically for a full-size 9MM pistol such as a stainless steel 1911, Browning Hi-Power, CZ 75 or SP-01, Canik clones, etc. +/- cash.  I will also consider other (mostly "tactical" type) firearms, but generally not hunting rifles or hunting shotguns, or antiques.  I am not desperate to sell.  Thank you.

title: For Sale:  Unfired High Standard Prototype
postcontent:
Unfired / New in box High Standard M-101 (2nd Generation Dura-Matic/1980's manufacture) .22lr semi-auto handgun w/ 4 1/2" barrel in matching box with all new factory goodies. Ordinary great-shooting handgun from yesteryear exemplifying American craftsmanship. Comes with never-used one-off factory prototype 6-inch threaded barrel with thread protector shroud. 

If you're into High Standard handguns, you already know these things are as solid as can be. No stamped metal in these babies - it's all solid, machined steel.  The slide feels like it's on ball bearings. Striker fire is much more dependable than cheap firing pins in modern semi-autos. This thing's a beast. 

Also comes with xtra 10 round mag (for a total of 2 mags), and all paperwork that came from factory is in box. 10/10 condition (no fingerprints, no rust, no marks, no wear - bluing is perfect - except for the areas on the spare 6" prototype threaded barrel where secondary machining was done; they left the metal bare naked where the threads were cut on the front of the barrel and where the front sight was modified; the thread protector also has yet to be blued). 1 picture limit sucks; this firearm is perfect inside & out! Threaded long barrel prototype is totally bizarre - I've never seen another one like it in all my years of collecting H/S handguns. Together they are one-of-a-kind. This barrel (unsure of thread size - I have many more pics available) is ready for suppressor and/or muzzle brake.

It would make a great safe queen or a great plinker. The handgun with 4 1/2" barrel was standard production run; should should perfectly first time out of the box, but the 6" barrel was obviously a work in progress. I cannot vouch for it since it has never been attached to the handgun and had a round fired through it.  Its value as a collector's item is certainly much more than its value as a 6" barrel. 

I don't know why I'm selling this thing. It just keeps calling out to me from the closet to "take me to the range" and I'm afraid one day I'm gonna do it. Get it away from me before I take it to the range and it's not new-in-the-box any more!

title: For Sale/Trade:  D Technik Waffen Werks VZ 58 vz58
postcontent: Well, it pains me to do this but my recent buys are forcing me to make a choice. I'm selling my Waffen Werks built VZ. This was the same company (along with TGI) to build Czechpoint guns before they took operations in house. Interestingly, Czechpoint is still using receiver blanks that were imported by Waffen Werks! This gun is built on a D Technik receiver and a D Technik kit. It features the original issue, cold hammer forged chrome lined barrel, and patented push down plate on the carrier. A few very nice features on this rifle, it has the bayonet lug and muzzle brake! Features many of the early builds did not have. Like all VZ rifles, it features a last round bolt hold open and milled receiver. They come in a full pound lighter than a stamped AK! It operates via a short stroke gas piston and fires via striker. It is also done in a finish that is a closer representation of the original. This rifle is and was very innovative for the time, and is considered a gold standard for auto loading simi auto 7.62x39 rifles! As always with used guns, there are light handling marks around the knob on the carrier and a few other spots. The barrel is bright and shiny with very strong rifling. The lower handguard on the bever barf has also been fitted with a Chris Stone heat shield. You will also receive a original issue bayonet and scabbard, sling, instructional DVD, cleaning kit, and two 922 compliant magazines. Have questions, please ask!
